Changed the field names in ArrowheadSystem to be more in line with the core system documentation. This makes it easier to use when creating the service registry and authentication entries

Changed the service provider to better use the ArrowheadSystem class. In particular, the ServiceProvider class keeps an reference to an ArrowheadSystem that stores the address and port. This separation is in line with the core systems, which can be seen in the _sr_entry and _auth_entry that now uses the ArrowheadClass with a simple conversion to JSON. However, it still needs to go through a function to keep the authenticationInfo away. I don't know if this is necessary or not but I'd rather not have that kind of information being always sent.

Added @property no_auth to arrowhead system to make it easier to not get authenticationInfo in certain places. Played around a little with the service provider to make it unable to authenticate when the consumer_system is empty. However, it probably should also belong in Authenticate(), as that is the actual function that should not be run.

Working on the consumer now, need to look more closely at the serviceRequestForm and make sure I can get it. Also, I need to make sure it looks up the orchestrator and authentication system's addresses so it only needs the service registry's to start.

Time examples are working as intended now.
However, some issues came up when working on the time example:
 - The core systems' uris are hard-coded in the service provider. The service provider should utilize the find_core_systems function in utils.
 - Creating post methods in the service provider either doesn't work or is very hard to do. This should be simplified.

Overall, the ServiceConsumer and ServiceProvider should be inheritable base-classes. I think that will solve the second issue above. Coding the CoAP/MQTT/etc. version of providers and consumers will be easier if that is the case as well.

Disbabled the certification check in the CertificateAccessPolicy because FastAPI/ASGI cannot provide the certificate unless it's running behind a reverse proxy. There's a proposal to add a header field with the certificate but it will take some time for that to be implemented. Also, this check is somewhat redundant as the server takes care of TLS before and everything that can get to there should already be safe.
